{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17635284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17635284"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:11:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:11:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17514"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17514","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17514"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0,0.77,0.09,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10204"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75027"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10204","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10204"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17514"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60534"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"5392"},{"type":"tags","id":"5395"},{"type":"tags","id":"7792"},{"type":"tags","id":"11724"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23883"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23998"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75027","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75027"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA research team wants to investigate whether regular exercise reduces the risk of developing type 2 diabetes. They plan to follow 10,000 adults without diabetes for 10 years, recording their exercise habits and monitoring for diabetes development.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes this study design?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ecological study","Cross-sectional study","Prospective cohort study","Randomised controlled trial","Case-control study"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a \u003Cstrong\u003Eprospective cohort study\u003C/strong\u003E design where a group of individuals without the outcome of interest (diabetes) are followed forward in time to examine the relationship between an exposure (exercise) and the development of the outcome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECase-control study\u003C/strong\u003E - This design would start with diabetic cases and non-diabetic controls, then look back at their exercise history\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECross-sectional study\u003C/strong\u003E - This would examine exercise habits and diabetes status at a single point in time\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERandomised controlled trial\u003C/strong\u003E - This would involve randomly assigning participants to exercise or no exercise groups\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEcological study\u003C/strong\u003E - This would examine population-level data rather than individual participants\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECohort studies are particularly useful for calculating incidence rates and relative risks, and can establish temporal relationships between exposure and outcome. However, they typically need a large sample size and lengthy follow-up.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cohort studies follow a group of individuals over time to examine the relationship between exposure and outcome.","Cohort studies are prospective (following participants forward in time) or retrospective (historical data).","Cohort studies are useful for calculating incidence rates and relative risks."],"referenc